# Documentation and standards – PandaTrack

When implementing new features or applying changes, follow these two practices so the project stays documented and consistent.

---

## 1. Document in `docs/` when it adds lasting context

Use the `docs/` folder for knowledge that helps future work and onboarding, not for every small change.

### Document in `docs/` when:

- **New module or area**: You add a new subsystem (e.g. auth, payments, a new app section). Create or update a doc that describes structure, entry points, and how to extend it (similar to `docs/development/i18n.md`).
- **Design or architecture decision**: A choice affects how other code should be written (e.g. how we call APIs, how we handle errors in a new layer). Add a short note in an existing doc or a small ADR-style section (what we decided and why).
- **Convention or flow others must follow**: Any pattern that other developers (or the AI) should reuse (e.g. adding a new locale, adding a new page type). Document the steps and where to touch the code.

### Do not push to `docs/` for:

- Single function or component behavior; use **comments and JSDoc** in code (see quality-docs-cleanup rule).
- One-off or feature-specific details that do not affect other parts of the project.

### Structure in `docs/`:

- **`docs/product/`**: Product source of truth (overview, scope, workflows, roadmap, glossary).
- **`docs/development/i18n.md`**: i18n setup, structure, and how to add locales or namespaces.
- **`docs/development/og-images.md`**: OG image generation conventions and implementation notes.
- **`docs/process/`**: Delivery process standards (DoD, review checklist, AI workflow).
- **New areas**: Prefer one focused file per topic and place it in the nearest coherent folder.

When you add or update something in `docs/`, place it in the right file and keep the same style (short sections, code examples where useful, clear headings).

---

## 2. Create a new Cursor rule only when it is a recurring standard

Not every instruction should become a rule. Create a new rule only when it will guide future implementations in a consistent way.

When the user explicitly describes a pattern they want applied across the project, consider capturing it in a Cursor rule. That does not always mean creating a new file: depending on the case, it may be better to update an existing rule (e.g. `coding-standards.mdc`, `project-structure.mdc`) to add the new convention, so the rule set stays small and consistent.

### Create a new rule when all of the following are true:

- **Recurring**: It is a pattern that will apply again (how we write or structure code), not a one-off feature request.
- **Future-facing**: It describes how to do things from now on, not a single fix or single feature.
- **Concise and actionable**: It can be written in a short, clear way (ideally under 50 lines) with concrete do/don’t or examples.
- **No duplication**: It does not repeat or contradict an existing rule in `.cursor/rules/`. If it extends one, consider updating that rule instead of adding a new file.

### Do not create a new rule when:

- The instruction is about implementing a specific feature or fixing a single bug.
- The same idea is already covered (or could be covered) in an existing rule.
- It is a vague or one-time preference.

### Before adding a rule:

1. Check existing rules (e.g. `coding-standards.mdc`, `quality-docs-cleanup.mdc`, `project-structure.mdc`) to avoid overlap.
2. If in doubt, add a short comment in code or a note in the relevant `docs/` file instead of creating a new rule.
3. New rules live in `.cursor/rules/` as `.mdc` files, with a clear `description` in the frontmatter and focused content.

This keeps the rule set small and useful so that documentation and standards stay maintainable.
